    <span class="na">external</span><span class="pi">:</span> <span class="no">true</span></code></pre></figure>

<h3 id="adding-posts-and-pages">Adding Posts and Pages</h3>

<p>There are two main content layouts: <em>post.html</em> (for posts) and <em>page.html</em> (for pages). Both have large <strong>feature images</strong> that span the full-width of the screen, and both are meant for text heavy blog posts (or articles).</p>

<h4 id="feature-images">Feature Images</h4>

<p>A good rule of thumb is to keep feature images nice and wide so you donâ€™t push the body text too far down. An image cropped around around 1024 x 256 pixels will keep file size down with an acceptable resolution for most devices. If you want to serve these images responsively Iâ€™d suggest looking at the <a href="https://github.com/scottjehl/picturefill">Jekyll Picture Tag</a> plugin<sup id="fnref:2" role="doc-noteref"><a href="#fn:2" class="footnote" rel="footnote">2</a></sup>.</p>

<p>The two layouts make the assumption that the feature images live in the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">images/</code> folder. To add a feature image to a post or page just include the filename in the front matter like so.</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-yaml" data-lang="yaml"><span class="na">image</span><span class="pi">:</span>
  <span class="na">feature</span><span class="pi">:</span> <span class="s">feature-image-filename.jpg</span>
  <span class="na">thumb</span><span class="pi">:</span> <span class="s">thumbnail-image.jpg</span> <span class="c1">#keep it square 200x200 px is good</span></code></pre></figure>

<p>If you want to apply attribution to a feature image use the following YAML front matter on posts or pages. Image credits appear directly below the feature image with a link back to the original source.</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-yaml" data-lang="yaml"><span class="na">image</span><span class="pi">:</span>
  <span class="na">feature</span><span class="pi">:</span> <span class="s">feature-image-filename.jpg</span>
  <span class="na">credit</span><span class="pi">:</span> <span class="s">Michael Rose</span> <span class="c1">#name of the person or site you want to credit</span>
  <span class="na">creditlink</span><span class="pi">:</span> <span class="s">http://www.theevilgenius.tk</span> <span class="c1">#url to their site or licensing</span></code></pre></figure>

<h4 id="thumbnails-for-og-and-twitter-cards">Thumbnails for OG and Twitter Cards</h4>

<p>Post and page thumbnails work the same way. These are used by <a href="https://developers.facebook.com/docs/opengraph/">Open Graph</a> and <a href="https://dev.twitter.com/docs/cards">Twitter Cards</a> meta tags found in <em>_head.html</em>. If you donâ€™t assign a thumbnail the default graphic <em>(default-thumb.png)</em> is used. Iâ€™d suggest changing this to something more meaningful â€” your logo or avatar are good options.</p>

<h4 id="table-of-contents">Table of Contents</h4>

<p>Any article or page that you want a <em>table of contents</em> to render insert the following HTML in your post before the actual content. <a href="http://kramdown.rubyforge.org/converter/html.html#toc">Kramdown will take care of the rest</a> and convert all headlines into a contents list.</p>

<p class="notice"><strong>PS:</strong> The TOC is hidden on small devices because I havenâ€™t gotten around to optimizing it. For now it only appears on larger screens (tablet and desktop).</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-html" data-lang="html"><span class="nt">&lt;section</span> <span class="na">id=</span><span class="s">"table-of-contents"</span> <span class="na">class=</span><span class="s">"toc"</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span>
  <span class="nt">&lt;header&gt;</span>
    <span class="nt">&lt;h3&gt;</span>Contents<span class="nt">&lt;/h3&gt;</span>
  <span class="nt">&lt;/header&gt;</span>
<span class="nt">&lt;div</span> <span class="na">id=</span><span class="s">"drawer"</span> <span class="na">markdown=</span><span class="s">"1"</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span>
*  Auto generated table of contents
{:toc}
<span class="nt">&lt;/div&gt;</span>
<span class="nt">&lt;/section&gt;</span><span class="c">&lt;!-- /#table-of-contents --&gt;</span></code></pre></figure>

<h4 id="videos">Videos</h4>

<p>Video embeds are responsive and scale with the width of the main content block with the help of <a href="http://fitvidsjs.com/">FitVids</a>.</p>

<p>Not sure if this only effects Kramdown or if itâ€™s an issue with Markdown in general. But adding YouTube video embeds causes errors when building your Jekyll site. To fix add a space between the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&lt;iframe&gt;</code> tags and remove <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">allowfullscreen</code>. Example below:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-html" data-lang="html"><span class="nt">&lt;iframe</span> <span class="na">width=</span><span class="s">"560"</span> <span class="na">height=</span><span class="s">"315"</span> <span class="na">src=</span><span class="s">"http://www.youtube.com/embed/PWf4WUoMXwg"</span> <span class="na">frameborder=</span><span class="s">"0"</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span> <span class="nt">&lt;/iframe&gt;</span></code></pre></figure>

<hr />

<h2 id="theme-development">Theme Development</h2>

<p>If you want to easily skin the themesâ€™ colors and fonts, take a look at <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">variables.less</code> in <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">assets/less/</code> and make the necessary changes to the color and font variables. To make development easier I setup a Grunt build script to compile/minify the LESS files into <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">main.min.css</code> and lint/concatenate/minify all scripts into <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">scripts.min.js</code>. <a href="http://nodejs.org/">Install Node.js</a>, then <a href="http://gruntjs.com/getting-started">install Grunt</a>, and then finally install the dependencies for the theme contained in <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">package.json</code>:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash">npm <span class="nb">install</span></code></pre></figure>

<p>From the themeâ€™s root, use <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">grunt</code> to rebuild the CSS, concatenate JavaScript files, and optimize .jpg, .png, and .svg files in the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">images/</code> folder. You can also use <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">grunt watch</code> in combination with <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">jekyll build --watch</code> to watch for updates to your LESS and JS files that Grunt will then automatically re-build as you write your code which will in turn auto-generate your Jekyll site when developing locally.</p>

<p>And if the command line isnâ€™t your thing (youâ€™re using Jekyll so it probably is), <a href="http://incident57.com/codekit/">CodeKit</a> for Mac OS X and <a href="http://alphapixels.com/prepros/">Prepros</a> for Windows are great alternatives.</p>

